'''Ahmadiyya Hospital New bussa''' provides humanitarian services to the people of [[New Bussa]], Mokwa and its surrounding areas.

Ahmadiyya Muslim Hospital, Newbussa, Niger state was opened on 1 December 1997.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aophc.com/find-doctors-clinics--hospitals-in-nigeria-kastina-kebbi-kogi-kwara-nasarawa-niger-ogun--ondo-states.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-05-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924044004/http://www.aophc.com/find-doctors-clinics--hospitals-in-nigeria-kastina-kebbi-kogi-kwara-nasarawa-niger-ogun--ondo-states.html |archive-date=2014-09-24 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> Dr Malik Mudassar Ahmed (MBBS) was appointed as the First Medical Director of the Hospital while Dr Laiqa Fozia (MBBS) his wife started working as Gyne and Obs specialist.<ref>http://www.vanguardngr.com/2013/11/hypertension-diabetes-rise-lagos-hospitals-specialist/</ref> Initially Hospital opened with 12 bed inpatient facility a radiology department an operation theater and outpatient facility.

In November 2001 Dr Muhammad Saqib Ghumman (MBBS) was appointed as the second Medical Director of the Healthcare facility. In September 2005 Dr Mehboob Ahmed Rehan (MBBS)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mehboobrehan.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502071303/http://www.mehboobrehan.com/ |archive-date=2014-05-02 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> was appointed as the third Medical Director.

{{as of|2013}} the facility contained 25 beds, ER, outpatient clinic, Diabetes and Hypertension clinics, a medical and a Surgical unit and a Radiology Department. On an average 35 health care professionals work in the facility.

The hospital was started under the Majlis Nusrat Jahan Scheme which was started by the worldwide head of the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community, Mirza Nasir Ahmed in 1970 on his tour of west African countries.<ref>http://www.alislam.org/library/history/ahmadiyya/89.html</ref> The headquarters of the scheme is in Rabwah, Pakistan which is run by Secretary Majlis Nusrat Jahan from [[Rabwah]].<ref>http://allafrica.com/stories/200312050312.html</ref>

This main objectives of the Nusrat Jehan Scheme was to render educational, humanitarian and social services to the local community in African countries. Under the guidelines of this project doctors and teachers were sent to serve in Nigeria, Ghana, Liberia, Gambia, and Sierra Leone. At the start of the project 17 hospitals and 15 secondary schools were set up by the Ahmadiyya community.

{{as of|2004}} the scheme had 373 schools and 36 hospitals in 12 countries under its name.

Khaifatul Masih V, [[Mirza Masroor Ahmad]] visited the complex in 2008 during the Centenary Khilafat Celebration in Nigeria.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ahmadiyyanigeria.net/index.php/departments/sami-wa-basari-audio-visual/9-uncategorised/129-ahmadiyya-clinics-and-hospitals |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-05-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041702/http://ahmadiyyanigeria.net/index.php/departments/sami-wa-basari-audio-visual/9-uncategorised/129-ahmadiyya-clinics-and-hospitals |archive-date=2016-03-04 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>

